<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,158,1042]" pageId="8" pageNumber="587">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,219,158,183]" pageId="8" pageNumber="587">Male.</emphasis>
Four stridulatory files on first and second abdominal tergites, two on each tergite. Anterior file on first tergite short with 5 peg-like teeth. Second file, also on first tergite longer, more than twice the length of anterior file, slightly curved, with 13 peg-like teeth. Third file on second tergite curved, with 15 peg-like teeth; teeth more densely packed than second file; posterior file on second tergite nearly straight, with 19 peg-like teeth; teeth more densely packed than third file. Second to posterior files of subequal length.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,158,1042]" pageId="8" pageNumber="587">
Eighth abdominal tergite enlarged, longer than other tergites (
<figureCitation box="[884,974,333,358]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1917,1939]" captionTargetBox="[170,1440,193,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[170,1440,193,1890]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Melaneremus? bellus sp. nov.: head and pronotum in dorsal view (A); face in anterior view (B); anterior half of body in lateral view (C); stridulatory files on abdominal tergite (D); female abdominal apex in posterior view (E); ovipositor in lateral view (F); female subgenital plate in ventral view (G); male abdominal apex in dorsal view (H); and male abdominal apex in ventral view (I). Scale bars: 5 mm (C, F); 2 mm (A, B, H); 1 mm (D, E, G, I)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1441903/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="587">Fig. 4H</figureCitation>
). Ninth abdominal tergite forming a hood (
<figureCitation box="[159,252,369,394]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1917,1939]" captionTargetBox="[170,1440,193,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[170,1440,193,1890]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Melaneremus? bellus sp. nov.: head and pronotum in dorsal view (A); face in anterior view (B); anterior half of body in lateral view (C); stridulatory files on abdominal tergite (D); female abdominal apex in posterior view (E); ovipositor in lateral view (F); female subgenital plate in ventral view (G); male abdominal apex in dorsal view (H); and male abdominal apex in ventral view (I). Scale bars: 5 mm (C, F); 2 mm (A, B, H); 1 mm (D, E, G, I)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1441903/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="587">Fig. 4H</figureCitation>
). Tenth abdominal tergite with two processes in the middle; each process broadest at the base, internal margin straight while external margin converges, pointing ventrally and produce into a sclerotized and obtuse apex; with setae (
<figureCitation box="[291,376,441,466]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1917,1939]" captionTargetBox="[170,1440,193,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[170,1440,193,1890]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Melaneremus? bellus sp. nov.: head and pronotum in dorsal view (A); face in anterior view (B); anterior half of body in lateral view (C); stridulatory files on abdominal tergite (D); female abdominal apex in posterior view (E); ovipositor in lateral view (F); female subgenital plate in ventral view (G); male abdominal apex in dorsal view (H); and male abdominal apex in ventral view (I). Scale bars: 5 mm (C, F); 2 mm (A, B, H); 1 mm (D, E, G, I)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1441903/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="587">
Fig. 
<date box="[350,376,442,466]" pageId="8" pageNumber="587">4I</date>
</figureCitation>
). Epiproct concealed beneath tenth abdominal tergite (
<figureCitation box="[1031,1115,441,466]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1917,1939]" captionTargetBox="[170,1440,193,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[170,1440,193,1890]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Melaneremus? bellus sp. nov.: head and pronotum in dorsal view (A); face in anterior view (B); anterior half of body in lateral view (C); stridulatory files on abdominal tergite (D); female abdominal apex in posterior view (E); ovipositor in lateral view (F); female subgenital plate in ventral view (G); male abdominal apex in dorsal view (H); and male abdominal apex in ventral view (I). Scale bars: 5 mm (C, F); 2 mm (A, B, H); 1 mm (D, E, G, I)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1441903/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="587">
Fig. 
<date box="[1089,1115,442,466]" pageId="8" pageNumber="587">4I</date>
</figureCitation>
). Cercus long and slender, cylindrical and setose, curved internally at the posterior end, with acute apex (
<figureCitation box="[1045,1125,477,502]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1917,1939]" captionTargetBox="[170,1440,193,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[170,1440,193,1890]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Melaneremus? bellus sp. nov.: head and pronotum in dorsal view (A); face in anterior view (B); anterior half of body in lateral view (C); stridulatory files on abdominal tergite (D); female abdominal apex in posterior view (E); ovipositor in lateral view (F); female subgenital plate in ventral view (G); male abdominal apex in dorsal view (H); and male abdominal apex in ventral view (I). Scale bars: 5 mm (C, F); 2 mm (A, B, H); 1 mm (D, E, G, I)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1441903/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="587">
Fig. 
<date box="[1098,1125,478,502]" pageId="8" pageNumber="587">4I</date>
</figureCitation>
). Subgenital plate circa 2.5 times wider than long; anterior margin broadly concave; lateral margin slightly converging posteriorly, with some setae; posterior margin broadly emarginated, laterally forming a lobe where stylus is inserted (
<figureCitation box="[1205,1283,549,574]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1917,1939]" captionTargetBox="[170,1440,193,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[170,1440,193,1890]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Melaneremus? bellus sp. nov.: head and pronotum in dorsal view (A); face in anterior view (B); anterior half of body in lateral view (C); stridulatory files on abdominal tergite (D); female abdominal apex in posterior view (E); ovipositor in lateral view (F); female subgenital plate in ventral view (G); male abdominal apex in dorsal view (H); and male abdominal apex in ventral view (I). Scale bars: 5 mm (C, F); 2 mm (A, B, H); 1 mm (D, E, G, I)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1441903/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="587">
Fig. 
<date box="[1257,1283,550,574]" pageId="8" pageNumber="587">4I</date>
</figureCitation>
). Stylus short and stout, setose, with obtuse apex (
<figureCitation box="[554,633,585,610]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1917,1939]" captionTargetBox="[170,1440,193,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[170,1440,193,1890]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Melaneremus? bellus sp. nov.: head and pronotum in dorsal view (A); face in anterior view (B); anterior half of body in lateral view (C); stridulatory files on abdominal tergite (D); female abdominal apex in posterior view (E); ovipositor in lateral view (F); female subgenital plate in ventral view (G); male abdominal apex in dorsal view (H); and male abdominal apex in ventral view (I). Scale bars: 5 mm (C, F); 2 mm (A, B, H); 1 mm (D, E, G, I)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1441903/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="587">
Fig. 
<date box="[607,633,586,610]" pageId="8" pageNumber="587">4I</date>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,158,1042]" pageId="8" pageNumber="587">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,351,621,646]" pageId="8" pageNumber="587">Colouration.</emphasis>
Generally brown to orange brown. Head, including frontal rostrum and frons, generally brown; dorsum darker than genae and frons; maxillary palps and labrum pale brown; mandibles darker brown. Pronotum brown, with margins and sulci darker. Anterior and middle legs generally pale brown, including spurs; tibial spurs with white tips. Posterior legs also pale brown; spines on femur and tibia with black tips; tarsi pale. Thoracic segments pale brown; abdominal tergites brown, sternites pale brown in the middle and very pale at the sides.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,158,1042]" pageId="8" pageNumber="587">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,319,801,826]" pageId="8" pageNumber="587">Variation.</emphasis>
In addition to variations in the measurements and number of spines and spurs on legs, the numbers of teeth on each stridulatory file can also vary between individuals, sex, and between the left and right side of each individual. It will be of interest to investigate how variable the stridulatory files are within conspecifics as well as congeners, and to assess if characters of the stridulatory files can be useful for assessing species boundaries.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,158,1042]" box="[199,478,945,970]" pageId="8" pageNumber="587">
